  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Supporting Vulnerable Refugees and Local Communities in Cox&apos;s Bazar, Bangladesh, through Improved  Access to Health, Protection, and Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH) Services</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Over three and a half years have passed since the forced displacement of Rohingya men, women, boys and girls from Myanmar into Bangladesh. Early leadership exercised by the Government of Bangladesh, with the support of the international community, worked to mitigate and manage the ensuing humanitarian crisis in the southern district of Cox&#x2019;s Bazar. Despite resilience and resolve shown by the refugee community, there exists as of yet no viable solution to the crisis until a safe and voluntary return to Rakhine state is guaranteed. The Rohingya who sought refuge in Cox&#x2019;s Bazar, continue to face formidable challenges and require Protection and other life-saving humanitarian assistance, with COVID-19 and monsoon season in 2020 further exacerbating needs. This project contributes to the reduction of morbidity and mortality among refuges and host community by improving equitable access to and utilization of quality life-saving and comprehensive primary and secondary health services for all crisis-affected populations. It reduces protection threats and vulnerabilities and strengthens protection services to meet the protection needs of refugees and host community; and upholds the safety and dignity of Rohingya refugees through improved comprehensive water, sanitation and hygiene infrastructure and services.</narrative>
  </description>
